[Romans 3:23](../../../bib/kjv/rom003.htm#023.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_023">rom 3:23</span></span>

sinned

Sin, Summary:

The literal meanings of the Hebrew, and (Greek, "hamartanō", "sin,"
"sinner", etc), disclose the true nature of sin in its manifold
manifestations.

Sin is transgression, an overstepping of the law, the divine boundary
between good and evil ([Psa 51:1](../../../bib/kjv/psa051.htm#001).md);
([Luk 15:29](../../../bib/kjv/luk015.htm#029).md); iniquity, an act
inherently wrong, whether expressly forbidden or not; error, a departure
from right; ([Psa 51:9](../../../bib/kjv/psa051.htm#009).md); ([Rom
3:23](../../../bib/kjv/rom003.htm#023).md); missing the mark, a failure to
meet the divine standard; trespass, the intrusion of self-will into the
sphere of divine authority ([Eph 2:1](../../../bib/kjv/eph002.htm#001).md);
lawlessness, or spiritual anarchy ([Ti1
1:9](../../../bib/kjv/ti1001.htm#009).md); unbelief, or an insult to the
divine veracity ([Joh 16:9](../../../bib/kjv/joh016.htm#009).md).

Sin originated with Satan ([Isa
14:12-14](../../../bib/kjv/isa014.htm#012).md); entered the world through
Adam ([Rom 5:12](../../../bib/kjv/rom005.htm#012).md); was, and is,
universal, Christ alone excepted; ([Rom
3:23](../../../bib/kjv/rom003.htm#023).md); ([Pe1
2:22](../../../bib/kjv/pe1002.htm#022).md); incurs the penalties of
spiritual and physical death; ([Gen
2:17](../../../bib/kjv/gen002.htm#017).md); ([Gen
3:19](../../../bib/kjv/gen003.htm#019).md); ([Eze
18:4](../../../bib/kjv/eze018.htm#004).md); ([Eze
18:20](../../../bib/kjv/eze018.htm#020).md); ([Rom
6:23](../../../bib/kjv/rom006.htm#023).md) and has no remedy but in the
sacrificial death of Christ; ([Heb
9:26](../../../bib/kjv/heb009.htm#026).md); ([Act
4:12](../../../bib/kjv/act004.htm#012).md) availed of by faith ([Act
13:38](../../../bib/kjv/act013.htm#038).md); ([Act
13:39](../../../bib/kjv/act013.htm#039).md).

Sin may be summarized as threefold:

An act, the violation of, or want of obedience to the revealed will of
God;

A state, absence of righteousness;

A nature, enmity toward God.

[Romans 3:24](../../../bib/kjv/rom003.htm#024.md)

<span class="margnote"><span id="an_024">rom 3:24</span></span>

Redemption

Redemption, "to deliver by paying a price." The New Testament doctrine.
The New Testament records the fulfilment of the Old Testament types and
prophecies of redemption through the sacrifice of Christ. The completed
truth is set forth in the three words which are translated redemption

\(1\) Greek, "agorazo", "to purchase in the market." The underlying
thought is of a slave-market. The subjects of redemption are "sold under
sin" ([Rom 7:14](../../../bib/kjv/rom007.htm#014).md) but are, moreover,
under sentence of death; ([Eze 18:4](../../../bib/kjv/eze018.htm#004).md);
([Joh 3:18](../../../bib/kjv/joh003.htm#018).md); ([Joh
3:19](../../../bib/kjv/joh003.htm#019).md); ([Rom
3:19](../../../bib/kjv/rom003.htm#019).md); ([Gal
3:10](../../../bib/kjv/gal003.htm#010).md); and the purchase price is the
blood of the Redeemer who dies in their stead; ([Gal
3:13](../../../bib/kjv/gal003.htm#013).md); ([Co2
5:21](../../../bib/kjv/co2005.htm#021).md); ([Mat
20:28](../../../bib/kjv/mat020.htm#028).md); ([Mar
10:45](../../../bib/kjv/mar010.htm#045).md); ([Ti1
2:6](../../../bib/kjv/ti1002.htm#006).md); ([Pe1
1:18](../../../bib/kjv/pe1001.htm#018).md).

\(2\) Greek, "exagorazo", "to buy out of the market." The redeemed are
never again to be exposed to sale;

\(3\) Greek, "lutroo", "to loose," "to set free by paying a price" ([Joh
8:32](../../../bib/kjv/joh008.htm#032).md); ([Gal
4:4](../../../bib/kjv/gal004.htm#004).md); ([Gal
4:5](../../../bib/kjv/gal004.htm#005).md); ([Gal
4:31](../../../bib/kjv/gal004.htm#031).md); ([Gal
